[[File:Retoque denticulado.png|thumb|right|Drawing of tool with denticulate [[retouch (lithics)|retouch]]]] In [[archeology]], a '''denticulate tool''' is a [[stone tool]] containing one or more edges that are worked into multiple notched shapes (or teeth), much like the toothed edge of a saw.<ref>"[https://www.britannica.com/topic/Mousterian-industry Mousterian industry]". Encyclopædia Britannica</ref> Indeed, such tools have been used as saws, more likely for meat processing than for wood. It is possible, however, that some or all of these notches were used for smoothing wooden shafts or for similar purposes.
These tools are included in the [[Mousterian]] tool industry by [[Neanderthal]] culture, proceeded by small hand axes and [[Scraper (archaeology)|side scrapers]].<ref>"[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0305440310003857 Application of a new typological approach to classifying denticulate and notched tools: the study of two Mousterian lithic assemblages]". ''Journal of Archaeological Science'', Volume 38, Issue 3, March 2011. pp. 711-722 </ref>
