{{Infobox book <!-- Wikipedia:WikiProject Books --> | name = The She Spot | image = shespot cover.jpg | author = [[Lisa Witter]] and [[Lisa Chen]] | country = United States | language = English | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = Berrett-Koehler Publishers | release_date = June 1, 2008 | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]]) | pages = 288 | isbn = 978-1-57675-472-6 | dewey= 658.8/34082 22 | congress= HF5415.332.W66 W577 2008 | oclc= 213222933 }}
'''''The She Spot: Why Women are the Market for Changing the World &ndash; And How to Reach Them''''' is a 2008 [[non-fiction]] book by [[Lisa Witter]] and [[Lisa Chen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Why political candidates should be sucking up to women |author=Kate Harding |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/06/02/she_spot/ |newspaper=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=June 2, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2012}}</ref>
== Synopsis == ''The She Spot'' looks at the impact of women on [[social change]], and focuses on the influence women have had on the world, as well as on volunteering. The book incorporates several case studies, polls, and the potential for women to be underrepresented in these polls and studies. It also covers the potential mis-representation in marketing towards women.<ref>{{cite news |title=The she spot; why women are the market for changing the world--and how to reach them (Book review) |author= |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-183483734.html |newspaper=Reference & Research Book News |date=August 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref>
==Critical reception== Critical reception for ''The She Spot'' has been positive, with [[Publishers Weekly]] calling it a "thoughtful, helpful guide to nonprofit marketers".<ref>{{cite news |title=Nonfiction review - The She Spot: Why Women Are the Market for Changing the World—and How to Reach Them |author=[[Staff writer]] |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-57675-472-6 |newspaper=[[Publishers Weekly]] |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2012}}</ref> [[AdAge|AdAge's]] Matt Kinsey wrote that the book was "good fodder for discussion" but that he was unsure that Witter and Chen's "formula alone can commandeer a loyal female audience".<ref>{{cite news |title=Finding 'The She Spot' More Important Than You Thought |author=Matt Kinsey |url=http://adage.com/article/ad-and-marketing-book-reviews/finding-spot-important-thought/130170/ |newspaper=[[Advertising Age]] |date=August 6, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2012}}</ref> A review in [[ForeWord (magazine)|ForeWord]] magazine by Mary Spiro said that, "If one agrees with the premise that marketing has been male-centered or that the strategies they present are uniquely suited to impact women then this text offers plenty of practical advice for those courting female clientele" and that the end of chapter summaries offer "quick inspiration".<ref>{{cite news |title=The She Spot: Why Women are the Market for Changing the World--and How to Reach Them (Book review) |author=Mary Spiro |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-236034590.html |newspaper=[[ForeWord (magazine)|ForeWord]] |date=August 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 17, 2012|subscription=yes}}</ref>
